Terpenoids constitute a large group of natural products whose beneficial effects have already been appreciated by ancient Egyptians (

; 

). It is estimated that over 55 000 terpenoid structures have been identified so far (

), which is probably only a fraction of what can be found in Nature, making it the largest class of natural products. Terpenoids are derived from the universal 
C-
5 building blocks, dimethylallyl diphosphate (DMAPP) and isopentenyl diphosphate (IPP). In plants two pathways contribute to the supply of DMAPP and IPP. The cytosolic mevalonate (MEV) pathway is common to all Eukaryotes and Archaebacteria, whereas the methylerythritol phosphate pathway (MEP) is present in the plastids of plants, in Bacteria and in some Protozoa (

). The sequential condensation of DMAPP with IPP catalyzed by isoprenyldiphosphate synthases leads to the formation of the starting molecules that define the different classes of terpenes. The most common isoprenyl diphosphates are geranyl (GPP, 
C-
10), farnesyl (FPP, 
C-
15) and geranylgeranyl (
GGPP
, 
C-
20), although some 
cis
-isoprenyl diphosphates have been found to be substrates of terpene synthases (

; 

).

While the diversity and phylogeny of terpene synthases in Angiosperms and Gymnosperms has been extensively reviewed (

; 

; 

), including for diterpenes, there is comparatively little on CYPs. In one recent review, the oxidations by CYPs were presented as branching points in plant terpenoid biosynthesis (

). In this review we wish to focus on CYPs involved in plant diterpene biosynthesis with the aim to answer the following questions: 1) is there a relationship between the structural classes of diterpenes found across plant species and the CYPs that can oxidize them? 2) Are there trends in the phylogenetic distribution of CYPs that oxidize diterpenes?

The structural diversity of the diterpene backbone is generated by the family of diterpene synthases (diTPS). Recent excellent reviews cover this topic (
) and we will only briefly present the major diterpene structural classes and their origins here. Diterpene synthases metabolize (E,E,E,E) - GGPP , except for a few cases where nerylneryl diphosphate is used (
), to the 20- carbon backbones of all diterpenoids. Plant terpene synthases ( TPS ), and diTPS in particular, constitute a conserved protein family with characteristic amino acid motifs that are required for catalysis. Although non-seed plant lineages do contain TPS that show similarity to microbial TPS (
), the TPS in seed plants belong to one phylogenetic group. The ancestral plant terpene synthase was most likely a diterpene synthase, as suggested by the fact that the single functional terpene synthase in the moss
Physcomitrella patens
is a bifunctional diterpene synthase, PpCPS/KS, that produces ent -kaurene, 16-hydroxy- ent -kaurane as well as ent -beyerene and ent -sandaracopimaradiene (
;
). PpCPS/KS has two catalytic activities that act in sequence to generate the diterpene products. The first is an ent -copalyl diphosphate synthase (CPS) that uses GGPP as substrate. CPS belongs to the class II of terpene synthases that initiate cyclization by protonation of a carbon-carbon double bond (
). The second activity is a kaurene synthase (KS) that converts ent -copalyl diphosphate to ent -kaurene and 16-hydroxy- ent - kaurane. KS belongs to the class I terpene synthases that initiate cyclization by abstraction of the diphosphate group through a Mg 2+ -dependent reaction (
). This presumably ancestral bifunctional diTPS went through different evolutionary paths to give rise to the plant diterpene diversity that we observe in extant plant species. In Gymnosperms and early vascular plants (lycophytes), the bifunctionality was retained but through gene duplication events and neo-functionalization gave rise to diversification of products. Thus in conifers for example, diterpene resin acids are derived from diterpenes such as abietadiene or pimaradiene that are synthesized by bifunctional diTPS. Notably the neo-functionalization affected both the class I and the class II activities. The class II activity in bifunctional diTPS of the conifers evolved to produce ( + )-copalyl diphosphate, a stereoisomer of ent -copalyl diphosphate (
), or even in some cases copal-8-ol diphosphate, the precursor of cis -abienol, where the resolution of the cyclization reaction is achieved by water addition at the C- 8 position instead of a proton elimination as for copalyl diphosphate. The neo-functionalization of the class I activity gave rise to novel activities in terms of both substrates, e.g. to use the novel products of class II diTPS activities, and products. Thus from ( + )-copalyl diphosphate a number of tricyclic diterpenes can be synthesized including abietadiene, levopimaradiene and isopimaradiene (
).

In an alternative evolutionary path, the ancestral bifunctional diTPS duplicated and gave rise to independent class I and class II terpene synthases. This is the case for the biosynthesis of 
ent
-kaurene, the precursor of the gibberellin hormones in vascular plants, where CPS and KS are encoded by similar but distinct genes, pointing to the common origin of these two enzymes (

; 

). CPS and KS of the gibberellin biosynthesis are conserved throughout the evolution of vascular plants and typically encoded by single copy genes but, as with bifunctional diTPS, gene duplication events followed by neo-functionalization also gave rise to novel diterpene products (

). The separation of class I and class II activities thus provided a fertile ground for the diversification of diterpene products. Interestingly, this neo-functionalization of class I and class II appears to have occurred essentially in Angiosperms, where diterpene diversity is probably at its highest in plants (

). All the diterpene products that are produced by sequential class II and class I activities have in common a bicyclic core structure and have therefore been named “labdane-related” (

). Monofunctional class I diterpene synthases also evolved independently in several plant lineages. For example the taxadiene synthase of yew trees (

Taxus
sp.

) involved in the biosynthesis of the anticancer drug Taxol 

ª

uses 
GGPP
as a substrate and in one step carries out a complex multiple cyclization reaction (

; 

). In contrast to taxadiene synthase, which retains the overall α/β/γ structure of ancestral bifunctional diTPS, a clade of angiosperm-specific diTPS lost both the β and γ domains. In the nomenclature of 

augmented by 

, this includes the tps-a, tps-b and tps-g families. Tps-a diTPS enzymes reported so far cyclize 
GGPP
to macrocyclic structures of the cembrane or casbane 
type
(

; 

; 

; 

). An overview of the major groups of diterpene structures is shown in 
Fig. 1.

One important superfamily of decorating enzymes are cytochrome P450 monooxygenases (CYPs). These enzymes typically contain a heme and can be found in organisms of all taxa (

). In plants, they constitute the third largest multigene family and are considered as one of the main contributors to the chemical diversity of metabolites, not only because they are often promiscuous (

; 

). The reactions catalyzed by CYPs include oxidation, dehydration, dealkylation, C-C cleavage, desaturation, decarboxylation, dimerization, isomerization, reduction and ring extension reactions. Plant CYPs transfer two electrons from the co-factors NAD(P)H and atmospheric oxygen to their substrates. In most cases in plants a cytochrome P450 reductase (CPR) is required to support the electron transfer (

; 

).

Here, we have collected all CYPs that have been characterized from plant diterpene biosynthesis to date ( Table S1 ), and have subjected them to phylogenetic analysis using the maximum likelihood method ( Fig. 2 , Table S1 ). Our phylogenetic analysis includes CYPs of 20 sub-families from the CYP 71, CYP 72 and CYP 85 clans, which carry out the oxidation of diverse plant diterpene skeletons based on published literature. In total, this comprises 61 characterized CYPs, which catalyze the formation of 98 identified products ( Table 1 ). In most cases these are macrocyclic or labdane-related diterpenoids. Diterpene metabolism in plants is dominated by a few CYP clans, with the CYP 71 and CYP 85 clans being major contributors and fewer representatives from the CYP 72 clan. This is not especially surprising because the CYP 71 and CYP 85 clans combined comprise the majority of the CYP families in plants (
). Interestingly however, only few families within these clans are represented among the diterpene oxidizing CYPs ( Fig. 2 ). In the CYP 85 clan, only three families are represented: CYP 725 A involved in taxane biosynthesis from yew trees (
Taxus sp.
), CYP 720B from conifer diterpene resin acid (DRA) biosynthesis and CYP 88 A , which encodes the kaurenoic acid oxidase (KAO). CYP 725 A and CYP 720B are families specific to Gymnosperms, whereas KAO can be found in all plant families except Bryophytes (
). However, all three CYP families from the CYP 85 clan appear to be ancient CYPs, which most likely evolved early in the evolution of Gymnosperms and Angiosperms.

Little is known about the 
CYP
72 clan with only a few characterized members to date. They are involved in steviol biosynthesis and gibberellin catabolism pointing to the close relationship of specialized diterpene pathways and hormone metabolism (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). 
CYP
714 is the only family of this clan represented in the plant diterpene CYPs (
Fig. 2
).

In contrast, the CYP 71 clan, a clan that is unique to land plants and includes more than 50% of all plant CYPs (
;
), has been investigated to a much greater extent. The phylogenetic analysis of diterpenoid CYP 71 clan members reveals a split into hormonal pathway (kaurene oxidases, KOs), known from all plant families, and angiosperm specialized metabolism. The latter comprises Lamiaceae phenolic diterpene ( CYP 71BE, CYP 71D, CYP 76AH, CYP 76AK and CYP 76BK), rice phytoalexin ( CYP 71Z, CYP 76M, CYP 99 A , and CYP 701 A ), Euphorbiaceae diterpene ( CYP 71D and CYP 726 A ) and Solanaceae diterpene ( CYP 71BN and CYP 71D) biosynthesis. Within that clan, more than half of all known angiosperm CYPs involved in specialized diterpene metabolism belong to the CYP 76 family. The rest of the CYP 71 clan is provided by CYP 71 family members and a few genes from the CYP 99 family (see Fig. 1 ). Interestingly, evolution of CYP 71 and CYP 76 families took place before monocots and eudicots separated because family members can be found in rice (monocot) and Lamiaceae or Euphorbiaceae (both eudicots). In
Oryza sativa
(rice) however, duplication events gave rise to five kaurene oxidase-like (KOL) genes, of which only OsKO2 is active in gibberellin biosynthesis (
). Of the other OsKOL genes, only OsKOL4 was reported so far to contribute to specialized phytoalexin biosynthesis, thus providing a nice example of neo-functionalization from a duplicated gene (
). This indicates that gibberellin biosynthesis genes can serve as a sequence pool from which specialized CYPs can evolve. But our phylogenetic analysis shows that KOs ( CYP 701 A ) are generally not the common ancestor of specialized metabolic CYP 71 clan members despite their long evolutionary history. Indeed, KOs have been found in ancient plant species (e.g.
P. patens
) (
), and therefore most likely evolved long before the separation between Angiosperms and Gymnosperms ( Fig. 2 ).

The number of identified diterpenoids in reactions involving CYPs, exceeds the number of CYPs known to be involved in their synthesis. This can be due to substrate promiscuity or to the capacity to carry out oxidations at several positions on a given backbone, which is in effect a specific case of substrate promiscuity. CYP 725As are the least promiscuous diterpene CYPs, usually accepting only a single substrate. KOs, KAOs, CYP 76AKs, rice phytoalexin CYPs and Euphorbiaceae CYPs are somewhat more flexible, partly because they carry out multiple oxidations at a single C-position. This holds true, for example, for KOs which convert ent -kaurene to ent -kaurenoic acid with the alcohol and the aldehyde forms as intermediates (
). The most promiscuous CYPs from diterpene metabolism in planta are CYP 720Bs and CYP 76AHs, which tolerate a whole spectrum of related but slightly different substrates. For the CYP 720B subfamily, this was considered to result in an evolutionary advantage for plant survival (
;
;
). Whether the promiscuity of CYP 76AH enzymes also confers a selective advantage remains to be shown.

Supporting the hypothesis of high substrate and mechanistic specificity but low flexibility in essential metabolisms (
;
), KOs and KAOs from gibberellin biosynthesis selectively accept single substrates across plant species. However, investigations on the promiscuity of Arabidopsis thaliana KO (AtKO) and rice KO2 (OsKO2) gave additional insights into substrate selectivity in hormone metabolism (
). It was observed that KOs do exhibit some promiscuity, and this to a different extent for the Arabidopsis and the rice KOs. Thus, OsKO2 accepting three ent -CPP-derived substrates ( ent -kaurene, ent -isokaurene and ent -trachylobane) is much less promiscuous then AtKO reacting on six substrates derived from ent -CPP, six from syn -CPP and one from normal CPP. However, AtKO carried out mostly single hydroxylation on substrates other than ent -CPP, indicating that the applied substrates were not the preferred ones. Nonetheless, this shows that enzymes involved in the biosynthesis of conserved signaling molecules can exhibit a certain degree of flexibility with regards to substrate specificity. In the case of Arabidopsis, it is conceivable that the somewhat relaxed substrate specificity of KO came about because of the absence of other labdane-related diterpenoids. In contrast, in rice the presence of labdanoids related to gibberellins could have led to a selection of more selective KO to prevent interference between hormone and specialized metabolism.

To better understand the reaction mechanisms and substrate preferences, homology modelling of CYPs has come into focus. It provides theoretical knowledge to predict amino acids from the active center presumably involved in substrate binding and turnover. The selected amino acids can subsequently be mutated and the impact of the introduced mutations on substrate or product evaluated. Protein engineering was carried out by Ignea and colleagues who created a library of random mutations on selected amino acid residues in the active site of
Pinus taeda
abietadiene oxidase. The substrate preference was changed and the catalytic activity could be increased (
). In a recent study, the structures of 11-hydroxy ferruginol synthases ( CYP 76AH22-24) and ferruginol synthases ( CYP 76AH1) were modelled to identify amino acid residues that determine the capacity to further hydroxylate ferruginol. Three key amino acids were found to contribute to the substrate and product specificity of each enzyme. Reciprocal mutagenesis of these amino acids was sufficient to convert the ferruginol synthases activity into 11-hydroxy ferruginol synthases and vice versa (
). In the absence of any crystal structure of CYPs involved in plant diterpene biosynthesis so far, homology modelling and site-directed mutagenesis offer a suitable approach to determine the catalytic mechanism, but also to create novel enzyme activities using synthetic biology tools.

Phytoalexins represent a group of plant anti-microbial compounds which are produced upon biotic or abiotic stress. They originate from different metabolite classes and are found in many plant species (

; 

). Labdane-related phytoalexins and oryzalide-related compounds have been found so far only in 

Zea mays

containing kauralexins, and in rice, which produces oryzalexin S, momilactone 
A
and B, oryzalides A-C, phytocassanes A-E, oryzalexins A-F, oryzalic acids and oryzadiones (

; 

, 

). Rice phytoalexins are of potential medicinal interest due to their antibiotic activity (

). 
In vivo
they inhibit seed germination of surrounding plants and exhibit anti-fungal activity upon 

Magnaporthe grisea

infection (

; 

; 

; 

; 

).

The existence of metabolic gene clusters has now been confirmed in several plant species (
;
). The biosynthesis of rice diterpene phytoalexins provides a nice example because it is encoded by two metabolic gene clusters (
;
). On the one hand, OsCPS2 , OsKSL5-7 which code for kaurene synthase-like enzymes,
OsCYP 71Z6, OsCYP71Z7
and OsCYP76M5-8 form a multifunctional metabolic gene cluster for phytocassane and oryzalide biosynthesis on chromosome 2. On the other hand, the momilactone cluster comprises OsCPS4 , OsKSL4 ,
OsCYP99 A 2-3
and a short chain alcohol dehydrogenase called OsMAS (
;
;
). Co-induction of momilactone cluster genes upon elicitation with UV irradiation or chitin oligosaccharide from fungal cell walls is in agreement with their involvement in the same pathway (
).

The activity of class I rice diTPS KSL4, KSL5, KSL6, KSL7, KSL8 and KSL10 supplies syn -pimara-7,15-diene, ent -kaur-15-ene, ent -pimara-8 (14),15-diene, ent -cassa-12,15-diene, syn -stemar-13-ene and ent -sandaracopimaradiene, respectively (
;
). These labdanoid diterpenes are then potential substrates for oxidation by CYPs. While no CYPs are known yet for the biosynthesis of maize (
Zea mays
) kauralexins, diverse CYP families contribute to rice phytoalexin synthesis ( Fig. 3B ). Rice momilactone biosynthesis was proposed to proceed via syn -pimara-7,15-diene. It serves as substrate for OsCYP99 A 3, less so for OsCYP99 A 2, to
form syn
-pimaradien-19-oic acid in a three-step oxidation process. Although OsCYP99 A 3 also has activity on syn -stemodene to
form syn
-stemoden-19-oic acid, syn -pimara-7,15-diene is the favored substrate (
). The downstream biosynthesis to momilactones is only partially elucidated. It was proposed that this pathway goes along 3β- hydroxy-9βH-pimaradiene-19,6β- olide which is converted to momilactone A by OsMAS, a short-chain alcohol dehydrogenase/reductase (SDR), and finally oxidized to momilactone B (
;
;
).

Oryzalides A-C are antibacterial phytoalexins that derive from ent - kaur-15-ene. The entire pathway has not yet been clarified, but OsCYP71Z6 is a C 2 hydroxylase that acts on ent -kaur-15-ene en route to oryzalide A . The highly similar OsCYP71Z7 is a C 2 oxidase too, but reacts with ent -cassa-12,15-diene rather inefficiently. Therefore, it was assumed that the preferred substrate of OsCYP71Z7 is a different one, most likely downstream to phytocassanes A-E (
). Next to OsCYP71Z7, OsCYP76M7-8 (catalyzing hydroxylation at position C 12) and OsCYP701 A 8 (promoting oxidation at C 3α) are assumed to be involved in the biosynthesis of antifungal phytocassanes. Notably, OsCYP 701 A 8 (also known as OsKOL4) belongs to the family of kaurene oxidase-like enzymes, indicating a recent evolution from KO (see above) ( Fig. 2 ). OsCYP701 A 8 (=OsKOL4) also accepts ent -kaurene and ent -sandaracopimaradiene to produce 3α- hydroxy- ent -kaurene and 3α- hydroxy- ent -sandaracopimaradiene, respectively (
;
). It is not yet clear to what extent the remaining three OsKOLs ( CYP 701 A ) enzymes are involved in specialized diterpene metabolism in rice. For example, no activity on diterpene skeletons could be found for OsKOL5, but it is induced upon fungal infection (
).

3α- hydroxy- 
ent
-sandaracopimaradiene is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of anti-microbial oryzalexins A-F. OsCYP76M6 and OsCYP76M8, from the same genetic cluster as OsCYP71Z6-7, catalyze downstream-oxidation of 3α- hydroxy- 
ent
-sandaracopimaradiene to oryzalexin E and oryzalexin D, respectively (

