GAs are plant diterpene hormones that have essential functions in plant growth and development and are conserved in vascular plants dating their appearance to around 400 MYA (
). Nonvascular plants such as the moss
P. patens
can only produce ent -kaurenoic acid (
). CYPs are involved in the early steps of GA biosynthesis and provide ent -kaurenoic acid and subsequently GA 12 , a substrate for 2-ODD activity en route to bioactive GAs (
). As seen above in the case of the rice phytoalexins, not only did genes from specialized diterpenoid metabolism evolve from those involved in GA biosynthesis, but also some diterpenes share intermediates with those of the GA pathway. This is the case for example for steviol glycosides which branch off of ent -kaurenoic acid ( Fig. 3D ). Steviol glycosides constitute a group of compounds from
Stevia rebaudiana
that can taste as much as 300 times sweeter than sucrose and are therefore of high commercial interest (
). C 13-hydroxylation by
A . thaliana
CYP 714 A results in steviol en route to steviol glycoside biosynthesis, but no homologue has been identified from
S. rebaudiana
(
;
). CYP 714s are otherwise known as inactivating GA in planta and thereby contribute to controlling growth processes (
;
;
).

Diterpene resin acids (DRAs) together with mono- and sesquiterpenes constitute a highly efficient mixture, also known as oleoresin, to counter pests in conifers. Upon herbivory and pathogenic attack the oleoresin is secreted at the entry point to exert chemical defense mechanisms or to form a physical barrier. In addition to toxicity, DRAs can harden upon contact with air, thereby effectively sealing the wound (
). The compounds are also released upon mechanical wounding or treatment with methyl jasmonate, which mimic herbivory and associated defense signaling strategies (
;
;
). The involved genes, namely diTPS and CYPs, are upregulated upon those treatments (
;
;
;
). In this section we focus on CYPs involved in the formation of tricyclic DRAs because no CYPs from bicyclic DRA biosynthesis are known to date. The dominant catalyzers in the biosynthesis of tricyclic DRAs are CYP 720Bs from the CYP 85 clan that are unique to resinous conifers ( Fig. 3E ). They accept various olefinic precursors (abietadiene and abietadiene-like, pimaradiene and pimaradiene-like, palustrastradiene and dehydrabietadiene/abietatriene) or 13-hydroxy-8 (14)-abietene as substrates. The first identified family member was CYP 720B1 from
Pinus taeda
for which orthologues were later detected in the genomes of
Pinus contorta
,
Pinus banksiana
and
Pinus brutia
(
;
;
). Ro and colleagues identified its activity as a C 18 oxidase and could prove the promiscuity of the enzyme by performing assays with the substrates abietadiene (rather inefficient conversion), abietadienol, abietadienal, levopimaradienol, isopimara-7,15-dienol, isopimara-7,15- dienal, dehydroabietadienol and dehydroabietadienal. The closely related CYP 720B4 from
Picea sitchensis
is a C 18 oxidase too, but is much more promiscuous than CYP 720B1. Remarkably, it is able to oxidize in total 24 substrates to the corresponding C 18-acids (
). For example, PsCYP720B4 was recently reported to produce miltiradienic acid when co-expressed with TPS 9 and TPS 27 from
Tripterygium wilfordii ( Forman et al., 2017 )
.

Paclitaxel, also known as Taxol 

ª

, is a diterpenoid compound from yew species that possesses powerful anti-cancer activity (

). Its natural occurrence is limited to a maximum of 500 μg per gram dried yew needles and therefore reliable supply has proved challenging (

). At present, paclitaxel is produced either semi-synthetically from Baccatin III or other taxane derivatives which can be isolated in suitable amounts from yew needles (

; 

) or from 

Taxus

cell suspension cultures (

