Plant diterpenoids are one of the most important metabolic group contributing to plant fitness and displaying an enormous potential for pharmaceutical and industrial applications (

; 

; 

). The underlying chemical diversity is established first by diterpene synthases and is typically followed by oxidations and rearrangements, which are carried out essentially by CYPs that exhibit varying degrees of substrate promiscuity. To date, we understand some diterpene biosyntheses whose genes are sometimes organized in metabolic clusters. However, our knowledge is still limited because the elucidated pathways of some macrocyclic and labdane-related compounds represent only a small fraction of the diterpene metabolome in plants. For example, the biosynthesis of triptolide, tanshinones, clerodane and other diterpenoids still remains poorly understood. In some of the mentioned pathways the participating diTPS have been characterized, but the identification of downstream decorating enzymes still remains to be done (

; 

; 

).

One clear trend from our analysis is that CYPs able to oxidize a class of diterpene in one plant family or species often belong to a sub-family which has expanded within a taxonomic clade. Thus, the CYP 76AH and CYP 76AK families constitute prime candidates when mining for diterpenoid CYPs in Lamiaceae which have not been explored yet. Given the substrate promiscuity already observed for some members of these sub-families, one can speculate that additional CYP 76 members from the Lamiaceae are likely to carry out additional reactions on labdane-related backbones at C-positions for which no catalyst is available yet. Identification of novel candidate genes can be based on co-expression analysis and the presence of genomic clusters. However, provided higher-throughput methods for cloning and expression are available, members of specific CYP sub-families can be systematically screened for novel activities. Such methods have been developed in yeast, using conventional or Golden Gate cloning tools combined with yeast expression and have proven highly efficient at exploring the diversity of labdane-related biosynthesis or for the elucidation of the carnosic acid pathway and reconstituting it in yeast (
,
;
). This approach is well adapted to a high-throughput testing of CYPs on a given diterpene backbone. Recently, combinations of class II and class I diTPS resulted in the production of over 50 products, 41 of which were considered as novel (or “new to nature”) (
). Combinatorial biosynthesis of diterpenes has also been successfully established in bacterial systems, providing an alternative production platform to yeast (
;
). Thus, combining libraries of diterpene synthases and of pre-selected CYP families has the potential to result in the rapid production of hundreds of novel diterpenoids, which can then be screened for biological activities of interest. When compounds with potential activity have been identified, their production can be further optimized to meet industrial standards. In that regard, the development of yeast strains producing the artemisinin precursor artemisinic acid with titers of 25 g / L culture (
) serves as a model for the engineering of other terpenoids and other natural products in yeast.
